  "text": "The spleen is the third most common location for hydatid cysts (0. 5%-8%), which itself is a rare disease. An isolated splenic involvement (primary) is seen in 2.6% cases, Figure 8 . A 54-year-old woman with splenic and hepatic hydatid cysts. A contrast-enhanced computed tomography shows a hypoattenuating lesion with peripheral wall calcification (Type V; white arrows) treated 26 years ago. There is also a hydatid cyst (black arrow) in the liver (L) parenchyma with peripheral focal areas of calcification Figure 9 . Coronal T2-weighted TSE magnetic resonance image shows a slightly heterogeneous hyperintense splenic mass with a low-signal intensity rim (white arrow), typical of a hydatid cyst. The black arrow indicates a hydatid cyst located at the dome of the right hepatic lobe (L) St: stomach Figure 10 . Changing cyst diameter before and after treatment whereas secondary invasion in any other organ such as the liver or lung is found in 20%-50% cases [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . In our study, 72% of the cysts were primary cysts and 28% were secondary cysts. The most rational explanation for the location of splenic hydatid disease is systemic circulation. Another explanation could be the retrograde flow through the portal vein, and a third explanation could be direct contagion from a neighboring organ's hydatid cyst [CITATION_3] 12) . Most patients with splenic hydatid disease may be asymptomatic because the cysts are slow-growing lesions, enlarging by only 1-2 cms in diameter every year. In our group, 44% of the patients had no symptoms. However, some patients may present with pain and/or meteorism. Some patients reveal palpable mass on the upper left quadrant and/or urticaria (1).",
